@node usage "How to use BMOD in AmigaOS"

There  is  a test loader included in the archive.  Its name is "bm".  It is
very  simple loader, and I just use it to test the BMOD routine.

You  can  convert  ProTracker© modules to BMODs equivalent by using program
called  "ptconv".  It saves the final BMOD module into T:moduli, so be sure
that you have that T:  assign.
@endnode

@node programming "How to use BMOD in your own productions"

I  think  you  have been waiting for read about this.  I have tried to make
BMOD  very easy to use in own productions and I think that I have succeeded
very well.  Okay, let's get into suburban mental state and start our voyage
to the borders of dimension..  =) (Quick note:  These instructions are very
obscure.)

First,  what  you  will  need  is  a  GOOD  compiler.   And I mean _A GOOD_
compiler.   It  has  to  handle  local  labels,  forcing  of  size operand,
non-forcing  of  already  forced  branches  (example:   jump  tables = .w),
optimizing non-forced branches.  I have been using SNMA by Samu Nuojua, and
it  is  _A  GOOD_ compiler.  It can handle all stuff mentioned before and a
lot  more.  I have included @{" some info about SNMA " link snma} into this guide, so you
can drool on your keyboard when reading SNMAs features.

Now,  when  you  have  already gotten _A GOOD_ compiler, we can start using
glue.   Some  important things to mention before including BMOD in your own
productions:

	1.	Your production has to keep system alive.
		If you want to get your production work in every possible
		configuration, you should use system atleast in minimum
		way. There are ways to keep system alive and get maximum
		available power from your Amiga. Also if you use system,
		your productions will very likely work in all Amigas
		and then you can be proud of your hard work.
		I have used many system routines in BMOD-initializing
		routines because they work in any configuration.

	2.	Don't modify any VBR-registers or customchips registers
		directly if possible. Your hacks might clash with BMOD.
		Use system routines to change VBR-base, then you don't
		have to think if VBR-base is in fastram.

	3.	Allocate your CIA/VBlank-interrupts with system routines,
		or you could kick BMODs play interrupt out of water.
		(Better yet, use timer.device)

	4.	Use newest possible includes available. Old includes
		have bugs.

	5.	Any ignoring of above simple rules might get you into
		trouble in someday, so beware!

Before  continuing,  check  the beginning of the player source (src/bmod.s)
and select options what you will need (or don't need).

Lets  go  on..   What  you  have to do next is, code a loading routine.  Or
equivalent.  In anycase, you have to do an initialized bmod_ModuleStructure
and  pass  it  to  InitPlayer.  When you look at BMOD module, you'll find a
header  (like  BMOD)  and  after  that comes a longword which tells you the
length  of  that section.  What you have to do is read the length after the
headerstring  and  read  the  section  in  memory  including  the  header +
length-fields.   Then  you  pass  the  pointer  to  that memory region into
bmod_ModuleStructure  and  process  to  the  next section.  Here is a quick
example how to code your loading routine.

     Init. Allocate a bmod_ModuleStructure.
	1. Read the length after the header.
	2. Allocate length + 8 bytes of memory.
	3. Pass the pointer of the allocated region into bmod_ModuleStructure.
	4. Read as many bytes as the length says plus 8 bytes (=the header)
	5. Now you are at the next header.
	6. If you have sections to go, jump to number 1 else go on.
	7. Now you have loaded the module and you can pass the
	   bmod_ModuleStructure pointer to InitPlayer.
	8. Check for possible errors and if any, just free
	   bmod_ModuleStructure and allocated modulesections, then do
	   your own errorhandling.
	9. Call PlayControl function with proper arguments.
	10. When finished, call EndPlayer.
	11. Free allocated bmod_ModuleStructure and modulesections.

Note:   The  regions  are  in  module  at  the  same  order  like  in
	bmod_ModuleStructure: BMOD, SINF, PINF, PATT, SMPL.

Note:	Allocate all modulesections with MEMF_PUBLIC!MEMF_CLEAR.

Note:   If all this looks very confusing, look @{" src/bm.s " link /src/bm.s/main} source for AmigaE
example. Also @{" src/bmod.i " link /src/bmod.i/main} has BMODs structures, which may clear things out.
@endnode

@node snma "SNMA macro assembler"
--info found in aminet--

Short:    680x0/6888x amiga macro assembler
Type:     dev/asm
Author:   snuojua@cc.helsinki.fi (Samu Nuojua)
Uploader: snuojua@cc.helsinki.fi (Samu Nuojua)

 SNMA  is freeware conditional 680x0/688x macro assembler for the Amiga.  It
 supports  the  most  common directives, generates Amiga object-files and/or
 executables.   It  is used mainly from the shell.  Arexx port.  AmigaOS 2.0
 and greater only.  AmigaGuide docs only.

--info found in SNMA.guide--

    My personal view on this assembler.
    (Things are not listed in any particular order)

    Good:

	- It's free (good for you).
	- Most common directives are supported.
	- Macros are supported.
	- All 680x0, 6888x, 68851 & 030/040 PMMU instructions are supported.
	- Does normal optimizations, including forward branches.
	- It's coded in assembler. (See below, Bad things).
	- Enforcer was in duty all the time I coded, checked, debugged...
	- Supports all data types of 680x0 6888x family (I think).
	  (FFP conversions are not supported).
	- ARexx interface.
	- Global symbol table
	- ARexx port

    Bad:
	- 68060 instructions (those few) are not yet supported.
	- All source files must fit into memory at the same time.
	- It's coded in assembler. Messy code sometimes - my fault, my
	  problem. (Moral: Assembly language is a two edged sword).
	- Some sort of beginner's help would be good (sources...).
	- Only output format is Amiga object code or executable.
	- No GUI, but I'm not so sure this would even be useful.
	- It's driving me crazy, sometimes.
@endnode

